1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,980
Now let's talk more about default parameter values,

2

00:00:02,980  -->  00:00:05,600
which are a backup plan for your functions.

3

00:00:05,600  -->  00:00:08,860
When you define a parameter with a default value,

4

00:00:08,860  -->  00:00:11,080
you don't have to pass an argument for it,

5

00:00:11,080  -->  00:00:14,980
as Python will use a default if nothing is provided for it.

6

00:00:14,980  -->  00:00:18,480
Think of default parameter values as a default setting,

7

00:00:18,480  -->  00:00:22,360
such as the default color for a car during checkout.

8

00:00:22,360  -->  00:00:27,540
If you specify that you want your car to have metallic red or night blue,

9

00:00:27,540  -->  00:00:31,680
that is a selection that will be an argument put into your function.

10

00:00:31,680  -->  00:00:34,000
But if you don't specify a color,

11

00:00:34,000  -->  00:00:37,560
the default value could be set as shiny silver,

12

00:00:37,560  -->  00:00:40,570
which will mean the car will be made with

13

00:00:40,570  -->  00:00:44,610
this default color value instead of a specific color.

14

00:00:44,610  -->  00:00:49,850
This feature of having a default makes functions more flexible and reduces the need for

15

00:00:49,850  -->  00:00:52,430
repetitive arguments because it will always be

16

00:00:52,430  -->  00:00:56,330
a fallback option that will be dynamically used automatically.

17

00:00:56,330  -->  00:01:00,050
Just remember that parameters with default values should be placed

18

00:01:00,050  -->  00:01:04,130
after those with defaults in the function signature.

19

00:01:04,130  -->  00:01:08,285
Let's see this more clearly in an example next.

20

00:01:08,285  -->  00:01:11,640
Let's look at default parameter values.

21

00:01:11,640  -->  00:01:14,140
Imagine you're building a car generator function,

22

00:01:14,140  -->  00:01:19,460
and one of the parts allows a user to customize the color of the car before checkout.

23

00:01:19,460  -->  00:01:24,720
We could define something like this where we define a choose_car_color function,

24

00:01:24,720  -->  00:01:27,570
and it takes a parameter of selected_color.

25

00:01:27,570  -->  00:01:29,920
If we return an F string telling us what

26

00:01:29,920  -->  00:01:34,020
color the car will be based on what the user selected,

27

00:01:34,020  -->  00:01:35,740
we might write something like this.

28

00:01:35,740  -->  00:01:39,400
We could say def choose_car_color,

29

00:01:40,490  -->  00:01:42,720
and then as a parameter,

30

00:01:42,720  -->  00:01:47,475
we'll say selected_color as an input,

31

00:01:47,475  -->  00:01:51,940
and then we'll return an F string, and we'll say,

32

00:01:51,940  -->  00:01:55,570
the car color will be, colon,

33

00:01:55,570  -->  00:02:03,840
and we'll pass in selected color and squiggly brackets, and we'll close that out.

34

00:02:03,840  -->  00:02:06,990
Now, if we press "Shift" and "Enter",

35

00:02:06,990  -->  00:02:10,195
we'll save this function to our Jupyter Notebook.

36

00:02:10,195  -->  00:02:12,520
However, this doesn't have a backup plan.

37

00:02:12,520  -->  00:02:17,120
If the user didn't select the color and the function is run like this,

38

00:02:17,120  -->  00:02:20,190
where we say, choose_car_color,

39

00:02:20,190  -->  00:02:22,160
and we try to execute this code,

40

00:02:22,160  -->  00:02:25,135
can you guess what will happen when we run this?

41

00:02:25,135  -->  00:02:28,790
Let's find out. When we run this,

42

00:02:28,790  -->  00:02:32,340
we'll get an error that's a type error, and it will say,

43

00:02:32,340  -->  00:02:37,720
choose_car_color missing one required positional argument, selected_color.

44

00:02:37,720  -->  00:02:40,510
This is because we are referencing an input parameter,

45

00:02:40,510  -->  00:02:42,330
but no argument was passed in,

46

00:02:42,330  -->  00:02:45,410
hence the error of the missing positional argument.

47

00:02:45,410  -->  00:02:49,050
We can avoid this error by adding a default parameter value

48

00:02:49,050  -->  00:02:52,870
for selected_color so that even if a user doesn't select a color,

49

00:02:52,870  -->  00:02:55,300
the car will still have a pre-loaded default,

50

00:02:55,300  -->  00:02:57,275
such as metallic red.

51

00:02:57,275  -->  00:03:01,500
What we can do is that we can pass in this default value

52

00:03:01,500  -->  00:03:10,100
here so that choose_car_color given this parameter,

53

00:03:10,100  -->  00:03:13,260
if we pass it in as an argument or not,

54

00:03:13,260  -->  00:03:16,620
it will have a default metallic red setting.

55

00:03:16,620  -->  00:03:21,670
Now if we save this cell to our Jupyter Notebook as a function,

56

00:03:21,670  -->  00:03:24,540
now if we run choose_car_color,

57

00:03:24,540  -->  00:03:29,280
the output will now say, the car color will be metallic red.

58

00:03:29,280  -->  00:03:33,000
If the user chooses a color like this,

59

00:03:33,650  -->  00:03:37,570
such as night blue,

60

00:03:39,050  -->  00:03:43,530
we'll now see the car color will be night blue.

61

00:03:43,530  -->  00:03:46,750
It's a good practice to get into the habit

62

00:03:46,750  -->  00:03:49,570
of adding in default parameter values if there is

63

00:03:49,570  -->  00:03:52,530
a system or program default or returning

64

00:03:52,530  -->  00:03:55,690
an error via an exception if no input is provided,

65

00:03:55,690  -->  00:03:59,150
and that is important to consider. Great work.
